{"actual_usd":0.159085,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":220,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31157,"reply":"\"No—though I get why it sounds that way at first.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square, wanting to answer cleanly instead of getting fancy with it.* \"Christians mean one Being, three Persons—not three separate beings who happen to share a category called godhood.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once.* \"If it were three independent centers of deity, that'd be three gods. But the claim is that the Father, Son, and Spirit are not three separate Gods standing side by side. They are the one God—fully, not fractionally—while remaining really distinct from one another.\"\n\n\"It's weird because we don't have a perfect human analogy for it.\" *The well chain gives a little clink in the morning quiet.* \"So the short answer is: not one God wearing three masks, and not three gods in a committee. One God, three Persons.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can try the longer version with the difference between 'being' and 'person,' because that's usually where the knot loosens.\"","rolling_24h_usd":34.62592000000002,"run_id":"5d5a3751-9be7-4f98-9372-2b4dc72e2ec1"}
